body:

make[1]: *** [CMakeFiles/Makefile2:1146: external/protobuf/cmake/CMakeFiles/protoc.dir/all] Error 2
make: *** [Makefile:141: all] Error 2
Traceback (most recent call last):

  File "/home/pi/devel/code/onnxruntime/tools/ci_build/build.py", line 1716, in main
    build_targets(args, cmake_path, build_dir, configs, args.parallel)
  File "/home/pi/devel/code/onnxruntime/tools/ci_build/build.py", line 871, in build_targets
    run_subprocess(cmd_args, env=env)

    env=my_env, shell=shell)

How do I disable onnxruntime logging in python?
body:
**Describe the bug**
Unable to disable the `onnxruntime` warnings at runtime

**Urgency**
none, just want to have a clean logger output from my application

**System information**
- Linux Mint
- ONNX Runtime installed from pip
- ONNX Runtime version:1.3.0
- Python version:3.6.9

**To Reproduce**
- Sample code to reproduce the issue.

I'm trying to use the face detector from [this](https://github.com/Linzaer/Ultra-Light-Fast-Generic-Face-Detector-1MB) repo.

Minimal code to reproduce the issue.
```
import onnx
import onnxruntime as ort 
from caffe2.python.onnx import backend

onnx_path = "/home/sujay/projects/ml_assets/face_detection/onnx/version-RFB-320.onnx"

print("loading")
predictor = onnx.load(onnx_path)
print("loaded")

onnx.checker.check_model(predictor)
onnx.helper.printable_graph(predictor.graph)
backend.prepare(predictor, device="CPU")

print("ort inference session")
# This is where warnings get printed
ort_session = ort.InferenceSession(onnx_path)
input_name = ort_session.get_inputs()[0].name
print("done loading")

```

What I've tried to resolve this issue by myself
1. Using the python `logging` module.
```
import logging
logging.basicConfig(format='%(filename)s %(message)s', level=logging.ERROR)
# This should technically have changed all logging to ERROR level, but it doesn't
``` 
2. `getLogger` approach
```
onnxlogger = logging.getLogger("onnxruntime")
onnxlogger.setLevel(logging.ERROR)
```
3. -W ignore flag
```
python -W ignore myscript.py
```
4. Using the `warnings` module
```
import warnings
with warnings.catch_warnings():
    warnings.simplefilter("ignore")
    # onnxruntime initialization code here 
```
5. From the [docs](https://microsoft.github.io/onnxruntime/python/api_summary.html), I tried to modify `onnxruntime.RunOptions` but that didn't help aswell
```
onnxruntime.RunOptions.log_severity_level=3 
onnxruntime.RunOptions.log_verbosity_level=3
```

The logs to dissappear

title: Fix subgraph based reshape fusion
body:
**Description**: #3931 added a new pattern for reshape fusion (Concat <-- subgraph <--root) by adding a shape value  of `-1` to the shape initializer for this pattern. This broke a 1PP model wherein a Shape node was feeding into the Concat. The Shape node would have produced multi-element data that was substituted with a `-1` and thus it tampered with the rank of the reshaped tensor when the Reshape was actually computed and broke downstream nodes.

Fix 1PP model

labels.name: type:enhancement
labels.description: request for unsupported feature or enhancement

body:
[DLPack](https://github.com/dmlc/dlpack) is an open in-memory tensor structure to for sharing tensor among frameworks. DLPack enables

Easier sharing of operators between deep learning frameworks.
Easier wrapping of vendor level operator implementations, allowing collaboration when introducing new devices/ops.
Quick swapping of backend implementations, like different version of BLAS
For final users, this could bring more operators, and possibility of mixing usage between frameworks.

DLPack is currently adopted by Tensorflow ([recently added](https://github.com/tensorflow/community/pull/180)), PyTorch, MXNet, CuPY, TVM, etc. Adding support for dlpack in onnx runtime will be beneficial in interoperability of ONNX runtime with the other deep learning frameworks.

title: fix build: pin pipeline Node.js version to 12.16.3
body:
pin Node.js version to 12.16.3 to fix build break.

This is a quick fix to unblock the build pipeline. There will be a complete fix to enable pipeline work with latest Node.js LTS.

why it broke the build?
- since 12.17, NAPI v6 is officially supported and the old macro `NAPI_EXPERIMENT` is removed and replaced by `NAPI_VERSION` 6. This cause the node.js binding to fail the build.

why not using NAPI v6?
- NAPI v6 is a very new API version so that onnxruntime would not work on some old Node.js version. **We are not really using any v6 features that implemented in Node.js recently.** The only feature we used in v6 is BigInt, which is already supported in Node.js 2 years ago. (the reason why BigInt is added in v6 is another story)

can current node.js binding work on latest and future Node.js without any code change?
- YES, it can. In our case, the NAPI v6 release only affect the typed array element type definition in `napi.h`. As explained above, the node.js already supported bigint 2 years ago and bigint64/biguint64 is already supported since then.

what is the plan for a complete fix?
- The goal is to make nodejs binding work with both old/new `napi.h` without declare the binding it self requires NAPI v6. This is kind of tricky but we want to support the current major node.js version. Details is still to be figured out.
